  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Προΐδων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "seeing before",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "prophetical",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " vision.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐλάλησε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he spake",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") in that 16th Psalm.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τοῦ Χριστοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "of Christ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Peter thus reasons: David did not speak of himself, as the fact shows; therefore he must have spoken of Christ, as being about to rise again from the dead. But how is the resurrection inferred from the promise concerning the kingdom? ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Answer",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Because Christ had not heretofore entered upon the kingdom, and because the future kingdom was an eternal one. Therefore David recognised the inner nature (character) of the kingdom of Messiah.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἡ ψυχὴ αὐτοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "His soul",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") The Latin Vulg. omits this. For it has “neque derelictus est in inferno;” where the masculine ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "derelictus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " shows that the translator has purposely written it so (and not by an oversight). Other very ancient authorities accord with this. More modern authorities have supplied it from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".[15]",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
